# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: playwright-testing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:playwright-testing/end-to-end-testing] System testing describes testing at the system level to contrast to testing at the system integration, integration or unit level.
[src:playwright-testing/end-to-end-testing] System testing often serves the purpose of evaluating the system's compliance with its specified requirements – often from a functional requirement specification (FRS), a system requirement specification (SRS), another type of specification or multiple.
[src:playwright-testing/end-to-end-testing] System testing can detect defects in the system as a whole.
[src:playwright-testing/end-to-end-testing] System testing can verify the design, the behavior and even the believed expectations of the customer.
[src:playwright-testing/end-to-end-testing] It is also intended to test up to and beyond the bounds of specified software and hardware requirements.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] A **headless browser** is a web browser without a graphical user interface.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] Headless browsers provide automated control of a web page in an environment similar to popular web browsers, but they are executed via a command-line interface or using network communication.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] They are particularly useful for testing web pages as they are able to render and understand HTML the same way a browser would, including styling elements such as page layout, color, font selection and execution of JavaScript and Ajax which are usually not available when using other testing methods.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] Since version 59 of Google Chrome and version 56 of Firefox, there is native support for remote control of the browser.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] This made earlier efforts obsolete, notably PhantomJS.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] Headless browsers are also useful for web scraping.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] Google stated in 2009 that using a headless browser could help their search engine index content from websites that use Ajax.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] However, a study of browser traffic in 2018 found no preference by malicious actors for headless browsers.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] There is no indication that headless browsers are used more frequently than non-headless browsers for malicious purposes, like DDoS attacks, SQL injections or cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] As several major browsers natively support headless mode through APIs, some software exists to perform browser automation through a unified interface.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] Some test automation software and frameworks include headless browsers as part of their testing apparati.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] Another approach is to use software that provides browser APIs.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] For example, Deno provides browser APIs as part of its design.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] For Node.js, jsdom is the most complete provider.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] While most are able to support common browser features (HTML parsing, cookies, XHR, some JavaScript, etc.), they do not render the DOM and have limited support for DOM events.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] They usually perform faster than full browsers, but are unable to correctly interpret many popular websites.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] Another is HtmlUnit, a headless browser written in Java.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] HtmlUnit uses the Rhino engine to provide JavaScript and Ajax support as well as partial rendering capability.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] These are various software that provide headless browser APIs.
[src:playwright-testing/headless-browser] An earlier effort (2008) was envjs from John Resig, which was a simulated browser environment written in JavaScript for the Rhino engine.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] Playwright Test is an end-to-end test framework for modern web apps.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] It bundles test runner, assertions, isolation, parallelization and rich tooling.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] Playwright supports Chromium, WebKit and Firefox on Windows, Linux and macOS, locally or in CI, headless or headed, with native mobile emulation for Chrome (Android) and Mobile Safari.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] Get started by installing Playwright using one of the following methods.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] The command below either initializes a new project or adds Playwright to an existing one.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] You can re-run the command later; it does not overwrite existing tests.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] You can also create and run tests with the VS Code Extension.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] Playwright downloads required browser binaries and creates the scaffold below.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] The playwright.config centralizes configuration: target browsers, timeouts, retries, projects, reporters and more.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] In existing projects dependencies are added to your current `package.json`.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] `tests/` contains a minimal starter test.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] By default tests run headless in parallel across Chromium, Firefox and WebKit (configurable in playwright.config).
[src:playwright-testing/intro] Output and aggregated results display in the terminal.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] See Running Tests for details on filtering, headed mode, sharding and retries.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] After a test run, the HTML Reporter provides a dashboard filterable by the browser, passed, failed, skipped, flaky and more.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] Click a test to inspect errors, attachments and steps.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] It auto-opens only when failures occur; open manually with the command below.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] Run tests with UI Mode for watch mode, live step view, time travel debugging and more.
[src:playwright-testing/intro] See the detailed guide on UI Mode for watch filters, step details and trace integration.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Locators are the central piece of Playwright's auto-waiting and retry-ability.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] In a nutshell, locators represent a way to find element(s) on the page at any moment.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] These are the recommended built-in locators.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Playwright comes with multiple built-in locators.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] To make tests resilient, we recommend prioritizing user-facing attributes and explicit contracts such as page.getByRole().
[src:playwright-testing/locators] For example, consider the following DOM structure.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Locate the element by its role of `button` with name "Sign in".
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Use the code generator to generate a locator, and then edit it as you'd like.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Every time a locator is used for an action, an up-to-date DOM element is located in the page.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] In the snippet below, the underlying DOM element will be located twice, once prior to every action.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] This means that if the DOM changes in between the calls due to re-render, the new element corresponding to the locator will be used.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Note that all methods that create a locator, such as page.getByLabel(), are also available on the Locator and FrameLocator classes, so you can chain them and iteratively narrow down your locator.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] The page.getByRole() locator reflects how users and assistive technology perceive the page, for example whether some element is a button or a checkbox.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] When locating by role, you should usually pass the accessible name as well, so that the locator pinpoints the exact element.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Role locators include buttons, checkboxes, headings, links, lists, tables, and many more and follow W3C specifications for ARIA role, ARIA attributes and accessible name.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Note that many html elements like `<button>` have an implicitly defined role that is recognized by the role locator.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Note that role locators **do not replace** accessibility audits and conformance tests, but rather give early feedback about the ARIA guidelines.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] We recommend prioritizing role locators to locate elements, as it is the closest way to how users and assistive technology perceive the page.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Most form controls usually have dedicated labels that could be conveniently used to interact with the form.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] In this case, you can locate the control by its associated label using page.getByLabel().
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Use this locator when locating form fields.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Inputs may have a placeholder attribute to hint to the user what value should be entered.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You can locate such an input using page.getByPlaceholder().
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Use this locator when locating form elements that do not have labels but do have placeholder texts.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Find an element by the text it contains.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You can match by a substring, exact string, or a regular expression when using page.getByText().
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Matching by text always normalizes whitespace, even with exact match.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] For example, it turns multiple spaces into one, turns line breaks into spaces and ignores leading and trailing whitespace.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] We recommend using text locators to find non interactive elements like `div`, `span`, `p`, etc.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] For interactive elements like `button`, `a`, `input`, etc. use role locators.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You can also filter by text which can be useful when trying to find a particular item in a list.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] All images should have an `alt` attribute that describes the image.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You can locate an image based on the text alternative using page.getByAltText().
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Use this locator when your element supports alt text such as `img` and `area` elements.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Locate an element with a matching title attribute using page.getByTitle().
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Use this locator when your element has the `title` attribute.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Testing by test ids is the most resilient way of testing as even if your text or role of the attribute changes, the test will still pass.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] QA's and developers should define explicit test ids and query them with page.getByTestId().
[src:playwright-testing/locators] However testing by test ids is not user facing.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] If the role or text value is important to you then consider using user facing locators such as role and text locators.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You can also use test ids when you choose to use the test id methodology or when you can't locate by role or text.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] By default, page.getByTestId() will locate elements based on the `data-testid` attribute, but you can configure it in your test config or by calling selectors.setTestIdAttribute().
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Set the test id to use a custom data attribute for your tests.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] In your html you can now use `data-pw` as your test id instead of the default `data-testid`.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] If you absolutely must use CSS or XPath locators, you can use page.locator() to create a locator that takes a selector describing how to find an element in the page.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Playwright supports CSS and XPath selectors, and auto-detects them if you omit `css=` or `xpath=` prefix.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] XPath and CSS selectors can be tied to the DOM structure or implementation.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] These selectors can break when the DOM structure changes.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] CSS and XPath are not recommended as the DOM can often change leading to non resilient tests.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Instead, try to come up with a locator that is close to how the user perceives the page such as role locators or define an explicit testing contract using test ids.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] All locators in Playwright **by default** work with elements in Shadow DOM.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You can locate in the same way as if the shadow root was not present at all.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Consider the following DOM structure where we want to click on the buy button of the second product card.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] We have a few options in order to filter the locators to get the right one.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Locators can be filtered by text with the locator.filter() method.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] It will search for a particular string somewhere inside the element, possibly in a descendant element, case-insensitively.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Locators support an option to only select elements that have or have not a descendant matching another locator.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You can therefore filter by any other locator such as a locator.getByRole(), locator.getByTestId(), locator.getByText() etc.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] The filtering locator **must be relative** to the original locator and is queried starting with the original locator match, not the document root.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] We can also filter by **not having** a matching element inside.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Note that the inner locator is matched starting from the outer one, not from the document root.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You can chain methods that create a locator, like page.getByText() or locator.getByRole(), to narrow down the search to a particular part of the page.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] In this example we first create a locator called product by locating its role of `listitem`.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] We can use the product locator again to get by role of button and click it and then use an assertion to make sure there is only one product with the text "Product 2".
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Method locator.and() narrows down an existing locator by matching an additional locator.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] For example, you can combine page.getByRole() and page.getByTitle() to match by both role and title.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] If you'd like to target one of the two or more elements, and you don't know which one it will be, use locator.or() to create a locator that matches any one or both of the alternatives.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] For example, consider a scenario where you'd like to click on a "New email" button, but sometimes a security settings dialog shows up instead.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] In this case, you can wait for either a "New email" button, or a dialog and act accordingly.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] If both "New email" button and security dialog appear on screen, the "or" locator will match both of them, possibly throwing the "strict mode violation" error.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] In this case, you can use locator.first() to only match one of them.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] It's usually better to find a more reliable way to uniquely identify the element instead of checking the visibility.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Consider a page with two buttons, the first invisible and the second visible.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You can assert locators in order to count the items in a list.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Use the count assertion to ensure that the list has 3 items.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You can assert locators in order to find all the text in a list.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Use expect(locator).toHaveText() to ensure that the list has the text "apple", "banana" and "orange".
[src:playwright-testing/locators] There are many ways to get a specific item in a list.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Use the page.getByText() method to locate an element in a list by its text content and then click on it.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Locate an item by its text content and click it.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Use the locator.filter() to locate a specific item in a list.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Locate an item by the role of "listitem" and then filter by the text of "orange" and then click it.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Use the page.getByTestId() method to locate an element in a list.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You may need to modify the html and add a test id if you don't already have a test id.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Locate an item by its test id of "orange" and then click it.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] If you have a list of identical elements, and the only way to distinguish between them is the order, you can choose a specific element from a list with locator.first(), locator.last() or locator.nth().
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Often times, the page might change, and the locator will point to a completely different element from the one you expected.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Instead, try to come up with a unique locator that will pass the strictness criteria.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] When you have elements with various similarities, you can use the locator.filter() method to select the right one.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You can also chain multiple filters to narrow down the selection.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You should now have a "screenshot.png" file in your project's root directory.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] The code inside locator.evaluateAll() runs in the page, you can call any DOM apis there.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] This means that all operations on locators that imply some target DOM element will throw an exception if more than one element matches.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] On the other hand, Playwright understands when you perform a multiple-element operation, so the following call works perfectly fine when the locator resolves to multiple elements.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] You can explicitly opt-out from strictness check by telling Playwright which element to use when multiple elements match, through locator.first(), locator.last(), and locator.nth().
[src:playwright-testing/locators] These methods are **not recommended** because when your page changes, Playwright may click on an element you did not intend.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] Instead, follow best practices above to create a locator that uniquely identifies the target element.
[src:playwright-testing/locators] For less commonly used locators, look at the other locators guide.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] Playwright provides the ability to automate browser tasks in Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit with a single API.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] It can also operate against branded browsers such as Google Chrome and Microsoft Edge available on the host machine, although these browsers are not installed by default.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] The current Playwright version supports Stable, Beta, Dev, and Canary channels of Google Chrome and Microsoft Edge.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] This allows developers to create reliable end-to-end tests that are capable of running in non-headless mode, as well as in headless mode for automation.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] Playwright supports programming languages like JavaScript, Python, C# and Java, though its main API was originally written in Node.js.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] It supports all modern web features including network interception and multiple browser contexts and provides automatic waiting, which reduces the flakiness of tests.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] Playwright was announced by Microsoft in January 2020.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] It was developed to address the need for a unified API for cross-browser testing and to overcome limitations in existing tools like Puppeteer, Cypress and Selenium.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] A team of engineers, including those who had previously worked on Puppeteer at Google, contributed to its development.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] Playwright introduced features like automatic waits, multi-browser support, and network interception, making it a powerful tool for modern web testing.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] Since its inception, it has been actively maintained and has seen rapid growth and adoption in the web testing community.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] The @playwright/test runner was released later as part of an effort to provide a more comprehensive solution for browser-based testing.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] Its development was largely based on the need to have a specialized runner that can leverage the full potential of the Playwright API and make end-to-end testing more robust and straightforward.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] Playwright is primarily used for automating browser tasks, which can range from simple page navigation and content scraping to more complex operations like automated form submissions, user interactions and more.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] In this example, Playwright is used to open a Chromium browser, navigate to `https://example.com`, take a screenshot and save it as `example.png`.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] @playwright/test further extends these capabilities by providing a test runner that allows developers to write and organize their tests in a more structured and scalable manner.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] In this example, a test is written to navigate to `https://example.com` and check that the title of the page is "Example Domain".
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] Reporters in Playwright define how test results are captured, aggregated, and surfaced after execution.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] They turn raw test events into structured output such as logs, files, dashboards, or external integrations, enabling teams to analyze trends, spot regressions, and debug failures more effectively.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] By centralizing errors, timings, traces, screenshots, and metadata, reporters make it easier to understand why tests failed, not just that they failed.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] Playwright includes built-in reporters and exposes a reporter API that supports both open-source and commercial implementations, which are listed below.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] As of 2025, Playwright is reported to have over 75,000 GitHub stars, more than 20 million NPM all‑time downloads, and over 11,000 Stack Overflow questions.
[src:playwright-testing/playwright-software] It has been described as experiencing the fastest growth in community adoption, GitHub stars, and modern usage among major web testing frameworks.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] Playwright includes test assertions in the form of `expect` function.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] To make an assertion, call `expect(value)` and choose a matcher that reflects the expectation.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] There are many generic matchers like `toEqual`, `toContain`, `toBeTruthy` that can be used to assert any conditions.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] Playwright also includes web-specific async matchers that will wait until the expected condition is met.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] Playwright will be re-testing the element with the test id of `status` until the fetched element has the `"Submitted"` text.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] It will re-fetch the element and check it over and over, until the condition is met or until the timeout is reached.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] You can either pass this timeout or configure it once via the testConfig.expect value in the test config.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] By default, the timeout for assertions is set to 5 seconds.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] The following assertions will retry until the assertion passes, or the assertion timeout is reached.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] Note that retrying assertions are async, so you must `await` them.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] These assertions allow to test any conditions, but do not auto-retry.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] Most of the time, web pages show information asynchronously, and using non-retrying assertions can lead to a flaky test.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] Prefer auto-retrying assertions whenever possible.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] For more complex assertions that need to be retried, use `expect.poll` or `expect.toPass`.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] These expressions can be nested in other assertions to allow more relaxed matching against a given condition.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] By default, failed assertion will terminate test execution.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] Playwright also supports *soft assertions*: failed soft assertions **do not** terminate test execution, but mark the test as failed.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] Note that soft assertions only work with Playwright test runner.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] This message will be shown in reporters, both for passing and failing expects, providing more context about the assertion.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] You can create your own pre-configured `expect` instance to have its own defaults such as `timeout` and `soft`.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] You can convert any synchronous `expect` to an asynchronous polling one using `expect.poll`.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] You can combine `expect.soft` with `expect.poll` to perform soft assertions in polling logic.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] This allows the test to continue even if the assertion inside poll fails.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] `expect.configure({ soft: true })` also chains with `expect.poll` and is useful when you want to reuse a configured instance.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] You can retry blocks of code until they are passing successfully.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] Note that by default `toPass` has timeout 0 and does not respect custom expect timeout.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] You can extend Playwright assertions by providing custom matchers.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] These matchers will be available on the `expect` object.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] In this example we add a custom `toHaveAmount` function.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] Custom matcher should return a `pass` flag indicating whether the assertion passed, and a `message` callback that's used when the assertion fails.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] Now we can use `toHaveAmount` in the test.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] Do not confuse Playwright's `expect` with the `expect` library.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] The latter is not fully integrated with Playwright test runner, so make sure to use Playwright's own `expect`.
[src:playwright-testing/test-assertions] You can combine custom matchers from multiple files or modules.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Playwright tests are simple: they **perform actions** and **assert the state** against expectations.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Playwright automatically waits for actionability checks to pass before performing each action.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] You don't need to add manual waits or deal with race conditions.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Playwright assertions are designed to describe expectations that will eventually be met, eliminating flaky timeouts and racy checks.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Take a look at the following example to see how to write a test.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Add `// @ts-check` at the start of each test file when using JavaScript in VS Code to get automatic type checking.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Most tests start by navigating to a URL.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] After that, the test interacts with page elements.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Playwright waits for the page to reach the load state before continuing.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Performing actions starts with locating elements.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Locators represent a way to find element(s) on the page at any moment.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Learn more about the different types of locators available.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Playwright waits for the element to be actionable before performing the action, so you don't need to wait for it to become available.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Here are the most popular Playwright actions.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] For the complete list, check the Locator API section.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Playwright includes async matchers that wait until the expected condition is met.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Using these matchers makes tests non-flaky and resilient.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Here are the most popular async assertions.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Playwright also includes generic matchers like `toEqual`, `toContain`, `toBeTruthy` that can be used to assert any conditions.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] These assertions do not use the `await` keyword as they perform immediate synchronous checks on already available values.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Playwright Test is based on the concept of test fixtures such as the built in page fixture, which is passed into your test.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Pages are isolated between tests due to the Browser Context, which is equivalent to a brand new browser profile.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Every test gets a fresh environment, even when multiple tests run in a single browser.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] You can use various test hooks such as `test.describe` to declare a group of tests and `test.beforeEach` and `test.afterEach` which are executed before/after each test.
[src:playwright-testing/writing-tests] Other hooks include the `test.beforeAll` and `test.afterAll` which are executed once per worker before/after all tests.
